# Response Variable Capture
# Demonstrates saving values from responses and reusing them in subsequent requests.
# Uses JetBrains HTTP Client syntax: > {% client.global.set("name", expression) %}
#
# Captured variables are saved to .http-client/.global-variables.json
# and persist across requests.

### Step 1: Make a request and capture values from the response
POST https://httpbin.org/post
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "username": "ada",
  "action": "login"
}

> {%
  client.global.set("origin", response.body.origin);
  client.global.set("request_url", response.body.url);
%}

###

### Step 2: Use captured variables in the next request
GET https://httpbin.org/anything
X-Origin: {{origin}}
X-Previous-URL: {{request_url}}

### ── Capture response headers ────────────────────────────────

### Capture a response header value
GET https://httpbin.org/response-headers?X-Request-Id=abc-123&X-Trace=trace-456

> {%
  client.global.set("request_id", response.headers.valueOf("X-Request-Id"));
  client.global.set("trace_id", response.headers.valueOf("X-Trace"));
%}

###

### Use captured headers
GET https://httpbin.org/headers
X-Correlation-Id: {{request_id}}
X-Parent-Trace: {{trace_id}}

### ── Capture HTTP status code ────────────────────────────────

### Capture the status code
GET https://httpbin.org/status/200

> {%
  client.global.set("last_status", response.status);
%}

### ── Capture nested JSON fields ──────────────────────────────

### Capture deeply nested values
POST https://httpbin.org/post
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "user": {
    "profile": {
      "name": "Ada Lovelace",
      "settings": {
        "theme": "dark"
      }
    }
  }
}

> {%
  client.global.set("user_name", response.body.json.user.profile.name);
  client.global.set("user_theme", response.body.json.user.profile.settings.theme);
%}

###

### Use deeply nested captured values
GET https://httpbin.org/anything
X-User-Name: {{user_name}}
X-User-Theme: {{user_theme}}

### ── Capture with static strings ─────────────────────────────

### Set a static value alongside dynamic ones
GET https://httpbin.org/get

> {%
  client.global.set("api_version", "v2");
  client.global.set("last_checked_ip", response.body.origin);
%}

###

### Use both static and captured variables
GET https://httpbin.org/anything/{{api_version}}/status
X-Client-IP: {{last_checked_ip}}

### ── Typical auth flow ───────────────────────────────────────
# This pattern works great with real APIs:
#
#   1. POST /login → capture token
#   2. GET /protected → use token
#
# Example (won't work against httpbin, but shows the pattern):
#
#   POST https://api.example.com/auth/login
#   Content-Type: application/json
#
#   { "username": "demo", "password": "secret" }
#
#   > {%
#     client.global.set("token", response.body.access_token);
#     client.global.set("refresh", response.body.refresh_token);
#     client.global.set("user_id", response.body.user.id);
#   %}
#
#   ###
#
#   GET https://api.example.com/users/{{user_id}}/profile
#   Authorization: Bearer {{token}}
